ass="css-1rtlxy" type="button" aria-label="close"><svg width="60" height="60" viewBox="0 0 60 60" fill="none"><circle cx="30" cy="30" r="30" fill="white" fill-opacity="0.9"></circle><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M38.4844 20.1006L39.8986 21.5148L21.5138 39.8996L20.0996 38.4854L38.4844 20.1006Z" fill="black"></path><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M21.5156 20.1006L20.1014 21.5148L38.4862 39.8996L39.9004 38.4854L21.5156 20.1006Z" fill="black"></path></svg></button><div class="css-rdbib0 e1drnplw1"></div><div class="css-18ow4sz e1drnplw2"><div aria-labelledby="modal-title" role="region"><header class="css-1bzlfz"><div class="css-mln36k" id="modal-title">transcript</div><button type="button" class="css-1igvuto"><div class="css-f40pzg"></div><span>Back</span></button><div class="css-f6lhej" data-testid="transcript-playback-controls"><div class="css-1ialerq"><button tabindex="99" type="button" class="css-1eut9gw" aria-label="play"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M8 13.7683V6L14.5 9.88415L8 13.7683Z" fill="var(--color-content-secondary,#363636)"></path><circle cx="10" cy="10" r="9.25" stroke="var(--color-stroke-primary,#121212)" stroke-width="1.5"></circle></svg></button><div class="css-1701swk"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 40 36" id="el_0kpS9qL_S"><title>bars</title><g id="el_oZ84Hna1GC_65hRV2Qwn" class="css-1fxvzwo" data-animator-group="true" data-animator-type="0"><g id="el_oZ84Hna1GC_ILVvi2tqx" class="css-1wnday1" ata-animator-group="true" data-animator-type="2"><g id="el_oZ84Hna1GC"><rect x="34" width="6" height="36" id="el_qw_T_tngXw"></rect></g></g></g><g id="el_mYVjkduhMU_p_9Pm85Ac" class="css-fwki7z" data-animator-group="true" data-animator-type="0"><g id="el_mYVjkduhMU_WxG3R40yd" class="css-t3i5e6" data-animator-group="true" data-animator-type="2"><g id="el_mYVjkduhMU"><rect x="22.67" width="6" height="36" id="el_lf9GrROk6j"></rect></g></g></g><g id="el_o-EuxhgoAw_kYNRGDfcw" class="css-t9te0w" data-animator-group="true" data-animator-type="0"><g id="el_o-EuxhgoAw_3c3bzSjOJ" class="css-1r5375t" ata-animator-group="true" data-animator-type="2"><g id="el_o-EuxhgoAw"><rect x="11.33" width="6" height="36" id="el_-iueO8klO0"></rect></g></g></g><g id="el_F7mSMPhqpC_y_fKcpSxn" class="css-qknaag" data-animator-group="true" data-animator-type="0"><g id="el_F7mSMPhqpC_R6bNB6_Ys" class="css-1ruvd04" ata-animator-group="true" data-animator-type="2"><g id="el_F7mSMPhqpC"><rect width="6" height="36" id="el_dS5TKNZZ5w"></rect></g></g></g></svg></div><div><div class="css-1t7yl1y">0:00<!-- -->/<!-- -->0:27</div><div class="css-og85jy">-<!-- -->0:00</div></div></div></div></header><div class="css-uzyn7p"><div class="css-1vxywau"><p class="css-1nng8z9">transcript</p><h2 class="css-9wqu2x">A Grand Ramp Inside Grand Central</h2><h4 class="css-qsd3hm">Each day, commuters hurry down a ramp hall at Grand Central Terminal with a few stopping to admire the view.</h4></div><dl class="css-p98d0w"><dt class="css-xx7kwh"></dt><dd class="css-4gvq6l"><p class="css-8hvvyd">n/a</p></dd></dl></div></div></div></div></div><div class="css-1cueeje" style="padding-bottom:56.25%;transition:opacity 300ms ease-in-out"><div class="css-1ihorw"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/15/nyregion/15blocks-video/15blocks-video-superJumbo.jpg" alt="Video player loading"/></div><div class="css-ew1078"><div class="css-ptry2i"><div></div><div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><figcaption class="css-1ifeaca e3rygrp0"><span class="css-jevhma e13ogyst0">Each day, commuters hurry down a ramp hall at Grand Central Terminal with a few stopping to admire the view.</span><span class="css-cch8ym"><span class="css-1dv1kvn">Credit</span><span class="css-1u46b97 e1z0qqy90"><span class="css-1ly73wi e1tej78p0">Credit...</span><span>Damon Winter/The New York Times</span></span></span></figcaption></figure><div data-testid="byline-timestamp" class="css-xt80pu eakwutd0"><div class="css-103l8m3"><div class="css-1e2jphy epjyd6m1"><div class="css-233int epjyd6m0"><p class="css-4anu6l e1jsehar1"><span class="byline-prefix">By </span><span class="css-1baulvz last-byline" itemProp="name"><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/by/david-w-dunlap" class="css-n8ff4n e1jsehar0">David W. Dunlap</a></span></p></div></div><div data-testid="reading-time-module" class="css-8atqhb"><ul class="css-1cgskve epjyd6m3"><li class="css-ccw2r3 epjyd6m2"><time class="css-1z1nqv e16638kd0" dateTime="2015-07-15T05:00:07-04:00">July 15, 2015</time></li></ul></div></div></div></header><section name="articleBody" class="meteredContent css-1r7ky0e"><div class="css-s99gbd StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Nothing has happened.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">That isn’t the most compelling way to begin a news column. But it <em class="css-2fg4z9 e1gzwzxm0">is</em> what makes the Oyster Bar ramp hall at <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://www.gcthistory.com/" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Grand Central Terminal</a> among the most imposing, dignified and humanistic public spaces in New York City.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">The <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/m/metropolitan_transportation_authority/index.html?inline=nyt-org" title="More articles about the N.Y. Metropolitan Transportation Authority.">Metropolitan Transportation Authority</a> has left it alone.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Vast enough for a good-sized cathedral — 302 feet long and 84 feet high — the ramp hall is the brilliant interstitial space, under chandeliers and skylights, between the main concourse and what was once the main waiting room on 42nd Street. Ample ramps converge from east and west. They meet at a great tiled vault, a whispering gallery with astonishing acoustical properties, under a bridge between the concourse and the old waiting room. The vault is a forecourt to the venerable Oyster Bar and the dining concourse.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">The grandeur of the ramp hall was seemingly lost in 1927, when the concourse ticket offices were expanded into a new mezzanine that reduced the triumphal portal to a rat hole. Until the 1990s, even the main concourse was a <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/20/nyregion/20thennow.html" title="">playground for advertisers</a>.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">All that changed in the 1998 reclamation of the terminal, designed by Beyer Blinder Belle. In the ramp hall, the mezzanine was removed and the bridge — once enclosed by eight-foot walls — was given a Beaux-Arts-style balustrade that opened up the space.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div></div><div class="css-s99gbd StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Almost nothing has happened since.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Enormous floor decals haven’t been slathered on the ramps. Jumbo LED billboards are not bolted into the walls. Placards do not hang from the bridge. In short, untold sums in advertising income have been left on the table, money that the Metro-North Railroad, a unit of the authority, could certainly use.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div><div data-testid="imageblock-wrapper"><figure class="img-sz-medium css-1hs5yzu e1g7ppur0" aria-label="media" role="group"><div class="css-1xdhyk6 erfvjey0" data-testid="photoviewer-children-figure"><span class="css-1ly73wi e1tej78p0">Image</span><img alt="" class="css-r3fift" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/15/nyregion/15blocks-1-web/15blocks-1-web-articleLarge.jpg?quality=75&amp;auto=webp&amp;disable=upscale" srcSet="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/15/nyregion/15blocks-1-web/15blocks-1-web-articleLarge.jpg?quality=75&amp;auto=webp 600w,https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/15/nyregion/15blocks-1-web/15blocks-1-web-jumbo.jpg?quality=75&amp;auto=webp 723w,https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/15/nyregion/15blocks-1-web/15blocks-1-web-superJumbo.jpg?quality=75&amp;auto=webp 1445w" sizes="((min-width: 600px) and (max-width: 1004px)) 84vw, (min-width: 1005px) 60vw, 100vw" decoding="async" width="600" height="851"/></div><figcaption data-testid="photoviewer-children-caption" class="css-gbc9ki ewdxa0s0"><span class="css-jevhma e13ogyst0">Broad ramps in Grand Central Terminal leading to the Oyster Bar.</span><span class="css-1u46b97 e1z0qqy90"><span class="css-1ly73wi e1tej78p0">Credit...</span><span><span aria-hidden="false">Damon Winter/The New York Times</span></span></span></figcaption></figure></div></div><div class="css-s99gbd StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">“We need to produce revenue to fix that leaky ceiling or that air-conditioning,” said George Monasterio, the railroad’s chief architect. But he also said Metro-North understood its role as the steward of a landmark.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">“We’re the first line of defense,” Mr. Monasterio said.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">As a result, Midtown Manhattan has an oasis of tranquillity where there is no sign of marketing or promotion — just hundreds of wanderers making their ceaseless way, absorbed by their inner lives or the faces of strangers because, for a moment, they <em class="css-2fg4z9 e1gzwzxm0">can</em> be.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">“It feels austere, yet elegant.”</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">These were the first words out of the mouth of <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://www.matthewbcrawford.com/new-page-1-1-2-1/" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Matthew B. Crawford</a>, the author of the newly published “<a class="css-yywogo" href="http://us.macmillan.com/books/9780374292980" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">The World Beyond Your Head</a>: On Becoming an Individual in an Age of Distraction,” as he stood at the top of the west ramp.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div></div><div class="css-s99gbd StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Mr. Crawford is a senior fellow at the <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://www.iasc-culture.org/" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Institute for Advanced Studies in Culture</a> at the University of Virginia. I invited him to take a look at the ramp hall during one of his visits to New York. I wanted to ask someone without a vested interest in saying so whether the hall was as special as I thought it was.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">“It makes me feel like I’m a citizen of something important,” he said. “It makes me feel as I imagine a citizen of Rome might have felt. I feel elevated.”</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Thoughts kept tumbling forth as we walked down the ramp.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">“From a certain perspective, this is just an inefficient use of space — if you can’t monetize it, it somehow isn’t real,” Mr. Crawford said.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div><div data-testid="imageblock-wrapper"><figure class="img-sz-medium css-d754w4 e1g7ppur0" aria-label="media" role="group"><div class="css-1xdhyk6 erfvjey0" data-testid="photoviewer-children-figure"><span class="css-1ly73wi e1tej78p0">Image</span><div class="css-nwd8t8" data-testid="lazy-image"><div data-testid="lazyimage-container" style="height:257.77777777777777px"></div></div></div><figcaption data-testid="photoviewer-children-caption" class="css-gbc9ki ewdxa0s0"><span class="css-jevhma e13ogyst0">Matthew B. Crawford, author of "World Beyond Your Head," said the hall made him feel like "a citizen of something important."</span><span class="css-1u46b97 e1z0qqy90"><span class="css-1ly73wi e1tej78p0">Credit...</span><span><span aria-hidden="false">Jake Naughton for The New York Times</span></span></span></figcaption></figure></div></div><div class="css-s99gbd StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">“It’s almost like walking into a cathedral or a church. It’s not a space for any of the concerns that we recognize as important, like commerce and efficiency.”</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div></div><div class="css-s99gbd StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Instead, it is more like what Mr. Crawford calls an “attentional commons,” a space where commercial interests do not try to wrest every precious bit of the public’s attention, allowing people the chance to — gasp! — interact with one another, even in silence.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Lest the authority or its advertising contractor, <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://www.outfrontmedia.com/whoweare/pages/aboutus.aspx" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Outfront Media</a>, be credited with too much civic enlightenment, it should be noted that keeping ads out of the ramp hall helps create what Outfront calls an “<a class="css-yywogo" href="http://www.outfrontmedia.com/whatwedo/products/digital/pages/grand-central-digital-network.aspx" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">uncluttered environment</a>” for the four big LED displays in the main concourse, increasing their value.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">The displays are further controlled “so you’re not bombarded with busyness,” Karen L. Timko, the agency preservation officer at Metro-North, said. Images must be static — no videos or animation. They cannot change more frequently than once every 15 seconds. All four must change at once. They must be dimmer than the nearby track indicators.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Because Grand Central is a landmark, the authority must review its plans for the building with the <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://nysparks.com/shpo/" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">State Historic Preservation Office</a>. It is hard to imagine that office going along with any proposal to install advertising in the ramp hall.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">“We wouldn’t even go to SHPO with that,” Ms. Timko said. “We wouldn’t let it get that far.”</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">In his book, Mr. Crawford writes, “The point of being aware of the attentional commons is not to make it happen but to refrain from damaging it.”</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">For more than 15 years, the Metropolitan Transportation Authority has refrained from damaging a subtle, precious civic resource. Yes, that’s news.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div></section><div class="bottom-of-article"><div class="css-19vx93s"></div><div class="css-13ldwoe">A version of this article appears in print on <span class="css-1dmwf73"> </span>, Section <!-- -->A<!-- -->, Page <!-- -->18<!-- --> of the New York edition<!-- --> with the headline: <!-- -->Tranquil Space in a Bustling Transit Hub<span>. <a href="https://www.parsintl.com/publication/the-new-york-times/">Order Reprints</a> | <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/section/todayspaper">Today’s Paper</a> | <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/subscriptions/Multiproduct/lp8HYKU.html?campaignId=48JQY">Subscribe</a></span></div><div role="toolbar" data-testid="share-tools" aria-label="Social Media Share buttons, Save button, and Comments Panel with current comment count" class="css-mfml7"><div class="css-10i3hc"></div><div class="css-jf7ug7"><ul class="css-1liwv7v"><li class="css-1gh9hw8"><div class="css-vxcmzt"><div class="css-79elbk"><button type="button" aria-label="" aria-expanded="false" class="css-1eeh360 actionbar-button" data-testid="gift-article-button"><span class="css-lu72is"><svg aria-hidden="true" width="19" height="19" viewBox="0 0 19 19" cla